–Overleden","1187–1226":"1187–1226","1180–1220":"1180–1220","1212–1292":"1212–1292","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1154–1251":"1154–1251","1155–1198":"1155–1198","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1251":"1251","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1155":"1155","before 1251":"vóór 1251","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Salkeld, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England":"Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1180–before 1251":"1180–before 1251","1180–1251":"1180–1251","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1187–1226":"1187–1226","1180–1220":"1180–1220","1212–1292":"1212–1292","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1154–1251":"1154–1251","1155–1198":"1155–1198","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1185":"1185","1251":"1251","1272":"1272","1292":"1292","1180":"1180","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1226":"1226","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1155":"1155","before 1251":"before 1251","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Salkeld, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England":"Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salkeld","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Salkeld (Cumberland), probably from Old English <i>salh</i> ‘willow, sallow’ + <i>hylte</i> ‘wood’, though the final element may have been confused with Old Norse <i>kelda</i> ‘spring, marshy place’. Alternatively, the final element may be an Old English <i>hilde</i>, a variant of <i>helde</i> ‘slope’. This surname has been present (though never common) in Ireland for centuries."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Salkeld was born in 1180, in Little Salkeld, Cumberland, England, his father, Thomas Salkeld, was 27 and his mother, Alicia Overton, was 26. He had at least 2 sons with Alice Huddlesceugh. He died before 1251, in his hometown."},"et":{"1180–before 1251":"1180–enne 1251","1180–1251":"1180–1251","1185–Male":"1185